Summary: This one isn’t a recent comic (it came out a month or so ago) but...
body:
Title: Peter Parker: The Spectacular Spider-Man #310

Summary: This one isn’t a recent comic (it came out a month or so ago) but it was too good not to mention now I’m blogging again. This issue is a stand alone story, that in my opinion, perfectly sums up what Spider-Man is all about. It has action, humour and heartbreak. Read this comic, you will not regret it.

Rating: 10/10 (I’d rate it higher than that if I could!)

body:
Title: Superior Spider-Man #1

Summary: I’m a huge Spider-Man fan and my favourite villain has always been Doctor Octopus. I loved the original Superior Spider-Man run and not surprisingly I enjoyed this. It was a good recap and set up issue without compromising on the storytelling. The art was really good too. Roll on issue 2!

Rating: 10/10

summary: I’m still thinking about Into the Spider-Verse because OMF that movie was one of the best I have ever seen? No exaggeration? But...
body:
I’m still thinking about Into the Spider-Verse because OMF that movie was one of the best I have ever seen? No exaggeration? But now specifically though I’m trying to understand why the movie was more marketed with the song Sunflower instead of What’s Up Danger? 

What’s Up Danger is just… superior in every way in my personal opinion. Not just the song (with a bonus being the relevancy of the lyrics,) but how it’s used. I had my fists squeezed so tight in thrill during that moment in the film. And I also saw a great post pointing out how it samples the same sound accompanied by Prowler and the meaning behind that, too? 

Also What’s Up Danger has the benefit of not having Post fucking Malone in it.
